column63: I used jupyter notebooks to prototype, verify, and understand a design for a viterbi decoder which was eventually accelerated in CUDA. First I built a super simple implementation that I knew produced correct outputs through building functions and updating them in their own cells, and manipulating data/running them in other cells. Then I prototyped the kernels for CUDA and made sure my python "kernels" produced correct output which combined to create a full decoder. Then I built my CUDA implementation with the python version as a reference for verification. I put data loading/saving functions in their own cells that I could run whenever code or data changed, and wrote comparison functions that would take the variables from the data manipulation cells and make sure everything worked as expected. I also used the inline plots from matplotlib to visualize my data alongside my code.

column63:
I have used Jupyter Notebooks for DATA 8, EE 16A, and DATA 100 assignments. I have also used Jupyter Notebooks while going through material from Stanford's CS 231n and Pieter Abbeel's Deep RL Bootcamp. These were guided Jupyter notebooks with some amount of skeleton code, and the process was usually reading and understanding the question and trying to fill in the gaps in the skeleton code. This usually involves reading a lot of documentation from different Python packages and creating extra test cells where I would enter some information and print out the output or try to see what sort of data I'm working with, until I iteratively arrive at a working solution.

I also used created Jupyter notebooks for a data science curriculum to be taught to students from under-sourced communities in India. This process started with formulating worksheets that these notebooks would complement, then finding appropriate data to illustrate basic data science concepts.

I can also describe a time I used Jupyter notebooks for a data analytics project as a SWE/data analytics intern. I started out by learning how to import in data and read a lot of matplotlib pyplot documentation to make some pretty presentable plots.
